   "source": [
    "# Research Question"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "How does emotional and cognitive intensity during autobiographical memory recall, measured by self-rated stress, mental drain, sentiment, and valence change, influence narrative detail and recall effort, measured by word count, memory duration, and writing time?\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Background and Prior Work"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Emotion has a significant impact on cognitive processes in humans, including attention, learning, and memory. The valence (positive or negative) and intensity (high or low) are differently related to autobiographical memories. 1 The emotional valence associated with autobiographical memories is important because positive memories tend to be recalled more frequently than negative memories. Previous research has found that autobiographical memories used for social functions tended to be positive, while memories recalled to direct future behaviors and decisions were the least positive ones.\n",
    "\n",
    "In a study that experimented with autobiographical memories that varied in valence and intensity, it was found that the emotional intensity affects the properties of autobiographical memories more than valence. 2 The study concluded that highly intense events tend to be remembered longer and with greater vividness.\n",
    "\n",
    "In a study on emotional intensity in episodic autobiographical memory and counterfactual thinking, it was found that emotional intensity during the remembered event was significantly higher for negative than positive events. 3 However, when remembering emotional events, there were no significant differences in emotional intensity between negative and positive memories. Additionally, the study evaluates episodic counterfactual thought, which is the act of imagining alternative ways that a past memory might have occurred. Memories can either be imagined to be better or worse than the events occurred, and accompanied by intense emotions. It was found that there was no difference in emotional intensity when remembering and emotional intensity participants imagined they would have during counterfactual events.\n",
    "\n",
    "Another study has also found that a perspective change from a field (first-person) to an observer (third-person) reduces the emotional intensity of recalled events. 4 Given the study above, a field-to-observer perspective change is likely to reduce the vividness of a memory. Furthermore, the study indicates that the autobiographical memory system has plasticity, and a perspective change alters the autobiographical records of recalled events.\n",
    "\n",
    "^ Tabea Wolf, Justina Pociunaite, Sophie Hoehne, Daniel Zimprich, The valence and the functions of autobiographical memories: Does intensity matter?, Consciousness and Cognition, Volume 91, 2021, 103119, ISSN 1053-8100, https://doi.org/10.1016/j.concog.2021.103119.\n",
    "^ Talarico, J.M., LaBar, K.S. & Rubin, D.C. Emotional intensity predicts autobiographical memory experience. Memory & Cognition 32, 1118–1132 (2004). https://doi.org/10.3758/BF03196886\n",
    "^ Matthew L. Stanley, Natasha Parikh, Gregory W. Stewart, Felipe De Brigard, Emotional intensity in episodic autobiographical memory and counterfactual thinking, Consciousness and Cognition, Volume 48, 2017, Pages 283-291, ISSN 1053-8100, https://doi.org/10.1016/j.concog.2016.12.013.\n",
    "^ Sekiguchi, T., & Nonaka, S. (2014). The long-term effect of perspective change on the emotional intensity of autobiographical memories. Cognition and Emotion, 28(2), 375–383. https://doi.org/10.1080/02699931.2013.825233"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Hypothesis\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Using an emotional intensity scale of 1-5, with no 0 values and self-rated importance of memory, we hypothesize that narratives reported as high in emotional intensity (≥4) and importance will be associated with greater vividness, more sensory detail, and more frequent use of a first-person perspective in the text, compared to narratives with lower and medium intensity ratings (0–3). This is based on the premise that experiences deemed more important or stressful to retell enhance memory encoding and recording of events, preserving detailed sensory and perspective information in autobiographical narratives.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Data overview\n",
    "\n",
    "Instructions: REPLACE the contents of this cell with your work, including any updates to recover points lost in your data checkpoint feedback\n",
    "\n",
    "- Dataset #1\n",
    "  - Dataset Name: HippoCorpus\n",
    "  - Link to the dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/saurabhshahane/hippocorpus?select=hippoCorpusV2.csv\n",
    "  - Number of observations: 6854\n",
    "  - Number of variables: 23\n",
    "  - Variables\n",
    "    - annotatorAge\n",
    "      - This is a key grouping variable. Since the dataset uses age buckets, we can compare patterns in story length, effort, and self reported ratings across age groups.\n",
    "    - Story\n",
    "      - This is the main text field (15 to 25 sentences). We can measure narrative detail using simple text based features such as word count and vocabulary diversity, and later explore whether the language differs across event types or intensity ratings.\n",
    "    - stressful, draining, & distracted\n",
    "      - These are ordinal 1 to 5 self reported ratings about the writing experience. We can treat stressful and draining as proxies for perceived intensity during recall, and distracted as a potential source of noise or reduced focus while writing.\n",
    "    - importance, frequency, similarity\n",
    "      - These are also ordinal 1 to 5 ratings, but they describe the event itself more directly.\n",
    "      - Importance captures how personal or impactful the event is.\n",
    "      - frequency captures how often they think or talk about the event, which could relate to how accessible the memory is.\n",
    "      - similarity captures how close the event feels to their real life, which may relate to engagement and detail.\n",
    "      - These variables are likely to be more informative for our question than stress alone because they describe the memory rather than only the writing process.\n",
    "    - logTimeSinceEvent and timeSinceEvent\n",
    "      - timeSinceEvent is the number of days since the recalled event happened, and logTimeSinceEvent is the logged version.\n",
    "      - Since the raw timeSinceEvent is extremely right skewed, logTimeSinceEvent is more useful for visualization and later modeling because it compresses extreme values and makes relationships easier to interpret.\n",
    "    - WorkTimeInSeconds\n",
    "      - This is total HIT completion time, including reading instructions, writing the story, and answering the follow up questions. Because it captures the entire task, it is better described as a proxy for overall effort rather than pure writing time. We can still compare it to word count and event intensity measures to see whether certain memories require more effort to complete.\n",
    "    - memType\n",
    "      - This variable describes the type of story provided by the participant. The dataset includes three possible categories: recalled, retold, and imagined. Recalled stories describe an actual personal memory, retold stories involve the participant recounting the same memory again, and imagined stories involve inventing a fictional event.\n",
    "      - Since this project focuses on personal memory recall and narrative retelling, imagined stories are removed from the analysis because they do not involve retrieving a real event from memory. The analysis therefore focuses on recalled and retold stories, which allows us to study differences in narrative detail and effort when participants describe real experiences.\n",
    "  - Descriptions of any shortcomings this dataset has with repsect to the project\n",
    "    - Everything here is self-reported and subjective (including age, stress and drain, and “distracted”), so it can be noisy and doesn’t directly measure mental exhaustion or memory accuracy.<br><br><br>\n",
    "      \n",
    "- Dataset #2 \n",
    "  - Dataset Name: Remembering Past Emotions \n",
    "  - Link to the dataset: https://ssh.datastations.nl/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.17026/SS/6EGKHT\n",
    "  - Number of observations: 625 segmented emotional memory recordings\n",
    "  - Number of variables: 54\n",
    "  - For this project, we will focus on variables that capture emotional intensity, memory recall, and the sentiment expressed while describing personal memories. Each observation represents a segmented portion of a participant’s autobiographical memory. The participant and gender variables provide basic demographic context, while the cue word identifies whether the memory is about a happy or sad experience. The emotional_memory_duration variable (converted to seconds) serves as a proxy for the level of recollection detail, since longer descriptions likely indicate more elaborate recall. Emotional experience is measured using past_valence and present_valence, which capture how positive or negative the event felt when it happened and how it feels now when being recalled, both on a scale from −1 (very negative) to +1 (very positive). Finally, sentiment_m and sentiment_sd quantify the emotional tone and variability of the language used during storytelling. The original study used an affective word lexicon where each emotional word received a score from −1 (negative) to +1 (positive). For each sentence in a memory segment, the mean sentiment score (sentiment_m) and the variability of sentiment (sentiment_sd) were calculated. So sentiment_m represents overall positivity/negativity of language, while sentiment_sd reflects variation in emotional wording."
   ]
  },
