   ],
   "source": [
    "mode_importance = hippo['importance'].mode(dropna=True)[0]\n",
    "hippo['importance'] = hippo['importance'].fillna(mode_importance)\n",
    "hippo['importance'].isna().sum()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As stated above, we will not impute for the frequency and similarity columns since they contain a large amount of missing data. What we can do right now is add a missingness indicator column (True or False) for both columns, which can help with analysis further down the line. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "hippo['frequency_missing'] = hippo['frequency'].isna()\n",
    "hippo['similarity_missing'] = hippo['similarity'].isna()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Is missingness associated with length or effort?**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x400 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Compare word_count and log_worktime between missing vs non-missing\n",
    "hippo['log_worktime'] = np.log1p(hippo['workTimeInSeconds'])\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12,4), sharey=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "sns.boxplot(data=hippo, x='frequency_missing', y='word_count', ax=axes[0])\n",
    "axes[0].set_title('Word Count vs Missing Frequency')\n",
    "axes[0].set_xlabel('frequency missing')\n",
    "\n",
    "sns.boxplot(data=hippo, x='similarity_missing', y='word_count', ax=axes[1])\n",
    "axes[1].set_title('Word Count vs Missing Similarity')\n",
    "axes[1].set_xlabel('similarity missing')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To better understand the missingness in the frequency and similarity variables, we compare story word counts between observations with missing values and those with reported values. For frequency, stories with missing ratings appear slightly shorter on average compared to those with observed frequency values. In contrast, stories where similarity is missing tend to have slightly higher word counts than those with reported similarity ratings. However, the distributions still overlap substantially in both cases, suggesting that while there may be small differences associated with missingness, the overall patterns in story length remain broadly similar.\n",
    "\n",
    "Because frequency and similarity contain substantial missingness and do not appear to produce dramatically different story length distributions, we choose not to impute these variables. Instead, analyses involving these variables will use only the rows where values are observed."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Outliers\n",
    "Using our main focus columns, we can look at a **standardized** box plot for each variable to get an idea of what the outlier data may look like"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1400x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "cols = [\"workTimeInSeconds\", \"word_count\", \"timeSinceEvent\", \"logTimeSinceEvent\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "df_plot = hippo[cols].copy()\n",
    "\n",
    "# standardize variables so they share the same scale\n",
    "df_z = (df_plot - df_plot.mean()) / df_plot.std(ddof=0)\n",
    "\n",
    "long = df_z.melt(var_name=\"variable\", value_name=\"z\")\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(14,6))\n",
    "sns.boxplot(data=long, x=\"variable\", y=\"z\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"Standardized value (z-score)\")\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"Outliers across continuous variables (standardized)\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We examine potential outliers in the main continuous variables by standardizing them using z-scores. Standardization places each variable on the same scale, allowing us to visually compare extreme observations across variables with very different ranges.\n",
    "\n",
    "The plot shows that timeSinceEvent contains extremely large outliers, with several observations far beyond the typical range of the dataset. This is expected because the time since a personal event can vary dramatically across individuals. These extreme values explain why the dataset also includes logTimeSinceEvent, which compresses the range of values and reduces the influence of these large outliers.\n",
    "\n",
    "In contrast, workTimeInSeconds and word_count show moderate right-tailed outliers, but their distributions are much more concentrated around the center. These higher values likely represent participants who took longer to complete the task or wrote unusually long narratives rather than data entry errors. Because these values appear to be part of the natural variability of the data, we retain them for analysis rather than removing them.\n",
    "\n",
    "Because timeSinceEvent contains extremely large values, the log-transformed version (logTimeSinceEvent) will be preferred in later analyses where recency of the memory is relevant."
   ]
  },
