  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The boxplots compare story word count across the three intensity ratings: stressful, draining, and distracted. Across all three variables, the distributions of word count overlap heavily and the medians remain relatively similar across levels. This suggests that perceived emotional intensity during recall does not strongly influence the length of the stories participants write. There is a slight upward shift in the median word count at the highest draining and distraction levels, which may indicate that more emotionally taxing memories lead to slightly longer narratives. However, the overall variability within each group is much larger than the differences between groups.\n",
    "\n",
    "All three plots contain numerous high word count outliers, showing that a subset of participants wrote substantially longer stories. At first glance, many of these long story outliers appear under lower intensity ratings, but the intensity variables are right skewed, meaning there are far more observations in the lower categories overall. Because of that imbalance, the concentration of outliers at lower ratings is likely driven by the higher number of responses there rather than a meaningful difference in story length across intensity levels. Overall, the word count distributions overlap heavily across ratings 1 through 5 for stressful, draining, and distracted, suggesting only minimal differences in story length by perceived intensity."
   ]
  },
