   "source": [
    "These boxplots compare story length (word_count) across three event level ratings: importance, frequency, and similarity. Unlike the intensity during writing variables, these measures show a more noticeable relationship with story length. As importance increases, the median word count increases and the upper range of word counts shifts upward, suggesting that more personally impactful events tend to be described in greater detail. A similar pattern appears for frequency and similarity: stories tied to events that participants think about more often or that feel more similar to their real life tend to be longer on average. Although the distributions still overlap across levels, the upward shift in medians across ratings indicates that these event level variables may be more informative predictors of narrative detail than stress related ratings.\n",
    "\n",
    "Because frequency and similarity contain substantial missing values, these boxplots reflect only the subset of stories where those ratings were provided. The visible trends should therefore be interpreted with that reduced sample in mind."
