   "source": [
    "### EDA Section 1 Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "Overall, the exploratory analysis suggests that narrative length varies moderately across participants but is not strongly driven by perceived task intensity such as stress or emotional drain. Instead, event-level characteristics such as importance, frequency of recall, and similarity to personal life show slightly stronger associations with story length, though these relationships remain relatively weak. Total task time is highly right-skewed but becomes more normally distributed after log transformation. While longer stories tend to require somewhat more time to complete, the relationship between writing time and story length is still modest. The correlation analysis also shows that measures of writing intensity, such as stressful and draining, are strongly related to each other but have little association with story length. Overall, these patterns suggest that narrative detail may be influenced more by the personal significance of the event than by the perceived difficulty of the writing task."
   ]
  },
